public abstract class ServicePanel
extends org.apache.wicket.markup.html.panel.Panel

Base type for all service panels. The constructor of this class takes only one argument, a ServicePanelDef object. Any information necessary for the creation of this panel should be passed via this service panel definition object.
Sub-classes of this class should only call super(definition) on their constructor and provide a suitable implementation for methods paint() and initialize(). The creation of a service panel is done in three steps. First the super constructor is called. Then the initialize() method is called. This method is the place where the creation of any component should take place. In case of class hierarchies of ServicePanels, each sub-class should call super.initialize(), in order to initialize any components declared in its super-class. Finally the paint() method is called. This method is supposed to combine components and set other properties of them. In case of class hierarchies of ServicePanels, each sub-class should paint all of its components, including the inherited ones, explicitly, because there is no guarantee that the component hierarchy assumed in its super-class is appropriate. This means that the use of the super.paint() call is discouraged.

paint

protected abstract void paint()
Paints this panel. This method should be called by the constructors of concrete sub-classes of ServicePanel. This method is the place to put the code that draws any visual components of this panel. Usually, this method should be one of the last things done by the class' constructor.

init

protected abstract void init()
Initializes the panel. This method should be called by the constructors of concrete sub-classes of ServicePanel. This method is the place to put the code that creates any visual components of this panel. This method should be called before calling paint(). Any call to super.initialize() should be the last statement of this method.

validateDef

protected void validateDef()
Validates the panel definition. This is the place to validate the panel definition and set defaults to any properties the user has not set and should not be null. This method is called before calling initialize(). Sub-classes should call super.validateDef() as a first statement.
